DATA 402 PROJECT 2

Pollen Grain Image Classification

Dataset Overview: This is a dataset from Kaggle The data can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/andrewmvd/pollen-grain-image-classification

About this data:

The classification of pollen species and types is an important task in many areas like palynology. This is the first annotated image dataset for the Brazilian Savannah pollen types. Article is: Feature Extraction and Machine Learning for the Classification of Brazilian Savannah Pollen Grains. Gonalves AB, Souza JS, Silva GGd, Cereda MP, Pott A, et al. (2016) Feature Extraction and Machine Learning for the Classification of Brazilian Savannah Pollen Grains. PLOS ONE 11(6): e0157044. https://doi.org/10.1371/journal.pone.0157044

Images by: Image by Thomas Schiewer at Pixabay

PCA shape: (790, 50) Total images: 790

The Objective

To accurately classify many of pollen grain images into their respective classes (no more than 10 clusters) This is important becausee challenges and machine learning skills can be implemented to real-life multi-class datasets like image classifciation for pollen grain. We can use this particular datasein order to display how it might interact with differe semi supervised and nonsupervied ML leaning methods. Howver, the goal is to ultimately be able to optimize clustering and image classification results to get optimal accuracy levels with different ML techniques. (I created this code in Google Colab)

Clarifications I want to make known

Non-supervised: K-means

Supervised: Artifical Neural Network (For some reason I mixed up terms in the video, but I do know what they mean).

In addition, L2 Regularization on ANN is a form of or extenstion of Supervised learning. Given the context, I counted that as two. The rubric didn't say I could not do this, it just said one should be some kind of artifical net...which I did. If I cannot do this, let me know, but that is my point of view given the class material.

#Function to extract DataFrame from a generator. Combination of HW 4 part a, HW 5 MINST section. Chatgpt did help me point out why errors were happening when my code wasn't working. Turns out I had a problem with 'filename' and accessing the images
def generator_to_df(generator):
    filenames = generator.filenames
    class_labels = [list(generator.class_indices.keys())[cls] for cls in generator.classes]
    return pd.DataFrame({'filename': filenames, 'class_label': class_labels})

#Creating Dataframes and generators, Train and Val from HW 4
train_pollen_df = generator_to_df(train_generator)
test_pollen_df = generator_to_df(validation_generator)

#Again the idea for laying out the content is inspired by Project 2 because I liked the aesthetic (the way train/split data is organized)
def print_train_test_amounts(train_data, test_data):
    print("\nThe Train/Test Split:\n---------------------")
    train_count = len(train_data)
    print("# of Train Images:", train_count)

    test_count = len(test_data)
    print("# of Test Images:", test_count)

    ratio = np.round(train_count / (test_count + train_count), 2)
    print("Train/Test Ratio:", ratio)

print_train_test_amounts(train_pollen_df, test_pollen_df)

import os
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from PIL import Image
import numpy as np

def display_train_image(pollen_class, train_pollen_df, dataset_path):
    if pollen_class in train_pollen_df['class_label'].values:
        #basically means came photos with their classes.
        indexes = [0, 2, 6]
        try:
            display_image_paths = train_pollen_df[train_pollen_df['class_label'] == pollen_class].iloc[indexes, 0]
        except IndexError:
            print(f"Not enough images for class '{pollen_class}'. Showing available ones.")
            display_image_paths = train_pollen_df[train_pollen_df['class_label'] == pollen_class]['filename'].head(len(indexes))

        #Three different classified images
        fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, len(display_image_paths), figsize=(15, 5), dpi = 40)

        for i, display_image_path in enumerate(display_image_paths):
            img_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, display_image_path)
            img = np.array(Image.open(img_path))

            axs[i].imshow(img)
            axs[i].axis('off')
            axs[i].set_title(f"Pollen: {pollen_class}\nPhoto #{indexes[i]}", fontsize=14)

        plt.show()

    else:
         print(f"Pollen class '{pollen_class}' not found in the DataFrame.")

def display_sample_images(paths, labels, dataset_name):
    class_paths = {}
    for path, label in zip(paths, labels):
        if label not in class_paths:
            class_paths[label] = []
        class_paths[label].append(path)

    #displaying the test and train images
    num_classes = len(class_paths)
    num_samples_per_class = 3
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_classes, num_samples_per_class, figsize=(12, 12))

    for i, (class_label, paths) in enumerate(class_paths.items()):
        sample_paths = paths[:num_samples_per_class]
        for j, path in enumerate(sample_paths):
            img = Image.open(os.path.join(dataset_path, path))
            axes[i, j].imshow(img)
            axes[i, j].set_title(f"Class: {class_label}")
            axes[i, j].axis('off')

    fig.suptitle(f'Sample Images from {dataset_name} Dataset', fontsize=16)
    plt.show()

import os
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt


#uploading the file within the file, to extract images from the 10 clusters I'd reduced from 21
def load_images(dataset_path):
    images = []
    for filename in os.listdir(dataset_path):
        if filename.endswith('.jpg'):
            img_path = os.path.join(dataset_path, filename)
            img = Image.open(img_path).convert('RGB').resize((256, 256))
            img_array = np.array(img) / 255.0  #0 to 1 range from hw 5
            images.append(img_array.flatten())  # Flatten and append from hw 4
    return np.array(images)

#here is where I'm loading these images. Taken from Hw 2 and also learnt in DAT 412 during split testing for tree classifcaiton.
X_train = load_images(dataset_path)
print("X_train shape:", X_train.shape)

#PCA dim reduction (Dat 402 PCA file)
pca = PCA(n_components=50)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)
print("PCA shape:", X_pca.shape)

#K-Means Clustering
num_clusters = 10  # Define the number of clusters you wish to use
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=num_clusters, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_pca)

#The cluster images need to be assigned labels before we plotthem
clusters = kmeans.labels_

# This part is taken from Dat 402 Classification Intro and Dat 402 K means homework.
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.hist(clusters, bins=num_clusters, edgecolor='black')
plt.title('Histogrm of Pollen Image Cluster Classification')
plt.xlabel('Cluster')
plt.ylabel('Number of Images')
plt.show()

centroids = pca.inverse_transform(kmeans.cluster_centers_)
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, num_clusters, figsize=(20, 2), subplot_kw={'xticks':[], 'yticks':[]})
fig.subplots_adjust(hspace=0.1, wspace=0.1)
for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flat):
    ax.imshow(centroids[i].reshape(256, 256, 3))
    ax.set_title(f'Cluster {i+1}')
plt.show()

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.metrics import silhouette_samples, silhouette_score

def plot_model_silhouettes(ax, model, X):
    # Get the labels from the model
    y_pred = model.labels_

    #silhouette scores for multiple k means
    silhouette_coefficients = silhouette_samples(X, y_pred)

    y_lower = 0

    for i in range(model.n_clusters):
        #silhouette scores
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values = silhouette_coefficients[y_pred == i]
        ith_cluster_silhouette_values.sort()

        y_upper = y_lower + len(ith_cluster_silhouette_values)
        color = plt.cm.jet(float(i) / model.n_clusters)
        ax.fill_betweenx(np.arange(y_lower, y_upper), 0, ith_cluster_silhouette_values,
                         facecolor=color, edgecolor=color, alpha=0.7)
        y_lower = y_upper + 10
    #silhouette score vertical line
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(X, y_pred)
    ax.axvline(x=silhouette_avg, color="red", linestyle="--")

    ax.set_xlabel("Silhouette coefficient values")
    ax.set_ylabel("Cluster label")

    #y-axis labels
    ax.set_yticks([])
    ax.set_xticks([-0.1, 0, 0.2, 0.4, 0.6])

##k=3 through 6 clusters
fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(15, 8))
axs = axs.flatten()

for i, model in enumerate(kmeans_models):
    plot_model_silhouettes(axs[i], model, X_pca)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

import os
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def display_images_from_clusters(dataset_path, clusters, cluster_ids, num_images=5):
    #Load all images and map them to their cluster ids. Taken from Project 2 example and ChatGPT did help explain to me how to embed my images after the fact I had errors in my code.
    image_paths = [os.path.join(dataset_path, filename) for filename in os.listdir(dataset_path) if filename.endswith('.jpg')]
    cluster_to_images = {i: [] for i in range(np.max(clusters) + 1)}

    for path, cluster_id in zip(image_paths, clusters):
        cluster_to_images[cluster_id].append(path)

    #plotting clusters from Hw 4
    for cluster_id in cluster_ids:
        if cluster_id in cluster_to_images:
            selected_images = np.random.choice(cluster_to_images[cluster_id], size=min(num_images, len(cluster_to_images[cluster_id])), replace=False)

            fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, num_images, figsize=(20, 4))
            fig.suptitle(f'Images from Cluster {cluster_id}', fontsize=16)

            for i, img_path in enumerate(selected_images):
                img = Image.open(img_path)
                axs[i].imshow(img)
                axs[i].axis('off')
                axs[i].set_title(f'Image {i+1}')

            plt.show()

display_images_from_clusters(dataset_path, clusters, [2, 8], num_images=5)

from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
from tensorflow.keras import layers, Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

num_clusters = 10  #i'm limited all my clusters to 10

#EarlyStopping is from hw 4(after ROC in HW)
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

#neural network architecture. Taken from HW 4 and partically what I was able to work with on HW 5. At least 3 layers as described in the rubric.
model = Sequential([
    layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(50,)),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(num_clusters, activation='softmax')  # Output layer with a unit for each cluster
])

#compiling model (hw 4 &5)
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])
model.summary()

from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

#Loading the data and split bit I got from HW 2.
X_train = load_images(dataset_path)

#Again, PCA in case images split wrong or something went wrong. I always want to reduce and ensure the size
pca = PCA(n_components=50)
X_pca = pca.fit_transform(X_train)

#K-means clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=10, random_state=42)
kmeans.fit(X_pca)

#Split the PCA-reduced data into training and validation sets. These are credited to my CIS 412 data modeling class as well Week 2 for split/testing principles as well as the second Hw.
X_train_pca, X_val_pca, y_train_pca, y_val_pca = train_test_split(X_pca, kmeans.labels_, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

#Most of this is taken from Hw 4 and 5 Part b & c
model = Sequential([
    layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(50,)),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')
])

#Compile the model (taken from Hw 4&5)
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

#Early stopping and fitting the model is taken from Hw 4
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

history = model.fit(
    x=X_train_pca,
    y=y_train_pca,
    epochs=100,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_data=(X_val_pca, y_val_pca),
    callbacks=[early_stopping],
    verbose=1
)

L2 Regularization on Neural Network (Reduce Overfit)

Adding penalty term to used to further prevent the overfit happening with our Nurual Network to improve Validation Accuracy Score. It's controlled by a hyperparameter and the idea is to be able to have a balance to fit the complexity, so I'm hoping to do that here

In[]:
from tensorflow.keras import regularizers

##L2 regularization. And I actualy got this idea while studying for Quiz 1. M4.10 Lasso (15:54) and I remember reading it in a book for CIS 412 class, don't know where. 

model = Sequential([
    layers.InputLayer(input_shape=(50,)),
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)),
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=regularizers.l2(0.001)),
    layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')
])

#Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

#Early stopping
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)

#Train the model
history = model.fit(
    x=X_train_pca,
    y=y_train_pca,
    epochs=100,
    batch_size=32,
    validation_data=(X_val_pca, y_val_pca),
    callbacks=[early_stopping],
    verbose=1
)

plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy')

plt.xlabel('Epoch')
plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
plt.legend()

plt.text(len(history.history['val_accuracy']), overall_val_accuracy, f'Overall Validation Accuracy: {overall_val_accuracy:.4f}', ha='right', va='center')

Conclusions

Overall, not the strongest clustering I wanted, but not -0. I managed to reduce the neural Network overfit by implementing a penalty for the model so takes in the small weights and doesn't overfit purely on the larger weights. Overall Validation Accuracy score of .824 is not bad, although it could've been better. I'm sure a convolutional neural network model would've been great, but it took me a long time to learn these topics. HW 5 was a great challenge. I unfortunately did not have time to implement convolutional neural network models, but overall an accruracy score is not bad. It's not near perfect, but not bad.

Classifers alone would not performed well with an siholoutte score closer to 0 than 1, and had if I added more than 10 clusters it would've make the entire project more complex and difficult to pin down. Because this is my first time using images, I did go a semi-safe route in terms of complexity/variation of the model so I had a fair chance of working it in two weeks.

In conslusion, my supervised learning and L2 regularization generated good results. I really enjoyed learning something new I've never done before. I plan on using these ML techiques more frequently, and I would be interested in seeing how this applies to more dirty data!
